I wouldn't even be able to keep
up with that conversations.

00:39:37.520 --> 00:39:39.380
I wouldn't even be able
to keep up with 83 groups.

00:39:39.380 --> 00:39:39.950
My goodness.

00:39:39.950 --> 00:39:41.033
THERESA GOH: It's so many.

00:39:41.033 --> 00:39:43.590
YIP PIN XIU: That's too many.

00:39:43.590 --> 00:39:45.660
I think it was 50-something
the last we checked.

00:39:45.660 --> 00:39:46.410
THERESA GOH: Yeah.

00:39:46.410 --> 00:39:46.951
It's growing.

00:39:49.360 --> 00:39:51.110
AUDIENCE: Thanks for
sharing your stories.

00:39:51.110 --> 00:39:53.900
It's really, really
inspirational.

00:39:53.900 --> 00:39:57.160
My question is, is
there any technology

00:39:57.160 --> 00:39:59.052
that has improved
your quality of life

00:39:59.052 --> 00:40:00.620
in terms of accessibility?

00:40:00.620 --> 00:40:05.590
And if not, what areas would
you like to see improving on?

00:40:05.590 --> 00:40:08.056
YIP PIN XIU:
Driverless technology.

00:40:08.056 --> 00:40:10.430
SPEAKER: I think it got stuck
there on Family and Friends

00:40:10.430 --> 00:40:12.490
Day.

00:40:12.490 --> 00:40:15.680
I just noticed that it's one
of the YouTube Kids ones.

00:40:15.680 --> 00:40:20.490
THERESA GOH: Does the-- that's
my-- it's not her phone.

00:40:20.490 --> 00:40:24.070
I can move along
with easily and fast.

00:40:24.070 --> 00:40:27.940
But I recently
bought this thing,

00:40:27.940 --> 00:40:30.040
the extra wheel at
the back of my chair

00:40:30.040 --> 00:40:32.050
that can connect and disconnect.

00:40:32.050 --> 00:40:34.880
And it helps me go up ramps.

00:40:34.880 --> 00:40:37.285
And so it's like a moto--

00:40:37.285 --> 00:40:38.160
YIP PIN XIU: A wheel.

00:40:38.160 --> 00:40:41.282
THERESA GOH: Yeah, so I just
push once and it will continue.

00:40:41.282 --> 00:40:43.341
YIP PIN XIU: Is it
like a Segway-ish?

00:40:43.341 --> 00:40:44.340
THERESA GOH: Not really.

00:40:44.340 --> 00:40:47.000
Segway, you got to lean, right?

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:48.910
No, this one doesn't lean.

00:40:48.910 --> 00:40:51.410
It helps to allow me
to move on carpets,

00:40:51.410 --> 00:40:55.700
because it's not so easy to
push a wheelchair on carpets.

00:40:55.700 --> 00:40:58.450
Like, little things like
that that doesn't necessarily

00:40:58.450 --> 00:41:01.810
make the chair heavier,
that much heavier,

00:41:01.810 --> 00:41:09.940
but it adds that extra
help that I need sometimes.

00:41:09.940 --> 00:41:13.270
YIP PIN XIU: So it's a
problem finding chairs,

00:41:13.270 --> 00:41:15.260
even the most basic of things--

00:41:15.260 --> 00:41:19.510
maybe for us, wheelchairs that
are at the same time slick,

00:41:19.510 --> 00:41:22.040
but at the same time
still have functions

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:24.190
that help with our lives.

00:41:24.190 --> 00:41:26.379
So everything's really bulky.

00:41:26.379 --> 00:41:27.962
THERESA GOH: The
lighter the chair is,

00:41:27.962 --> 00:41:29.003
the easier it is to push.

00:41:29.003 --> 00:41:31.760
But the lighter it is,
the more expensive it is.

00:41:31.760 --> 00:41:37.890
And that can be problematic
for the poorer countries.

00:41:37.890 --> 00:41:40.330
So a lot of times, you
find that the chairs that

00:41:40.330 --> 00:41:42.990
are massive and hospital
chairs, basically.

00:41:42.990 --> 00:41:44.570
And it's not easy to push.

00:41:44.570 --> 00:41:47.270
It's basically meant
for someone to push you.

00:41:47.270 --> 00:41:50.534
And then you remove
that independent factor.

00:41:50.534 --> 00:41:52.950
And then they have to depend
on other people to push them.

00:41:52.950 --> 00:41:56.950
And then it just becomes
a downward spiral.

00:41:56.950 --> 00:41:59.620
AUDIENCE: Thanks for
coming, Pin Xiu and Theresa.

