00:46:20.940 --> 00:46:22.739
very competitive-- comparative.

00:46:22.739 --> 00:46:24.030
YIP PIN XIU: But it's not true.

00:46:24.030 --> 00:46:25.830
Actually, it's just
that for Olympic sports,

00:46:25.830 --> 00:46:26.829
we are good at swimming.

00:46:26.829 --> 00:46:29.250
But bowling doesn't
have the Olympics.

00:46:29.250 --> 00:46:30.936
But we are very good bowlers.

00:46:30.936 --> 00:46:32.310
THERESA GOH:
World-level bowlers.

00:46:32.310 --> 00:46:33.500
YIP PIN XIU: Our bowlers
win world championships.

00:46:33.500 --> 00:46:35.420
THERESA GOH: But they just
don't have an audience.

00:46:35.420 --> 00:46:36.450
YIP PIN XIU: Yeah, they
just don't have an audience.

00:46:36.450 --> 00:46:38.470
And I think in order
to be a good athlete,

00:46:38.470 --> 00:46:43.230
it comes from the culture
of the sports itself.

00:46:43.230 --> 00:46:45.330
So some people--
say for swimmers, we

00:46:45.330 --> 00:46:47.300
have a lot of swimmers
to look up to.

00:46:47.300 --> 00:46:48.950
We know what they do.

00:46:48.950 --> 00:46:51.410
We know the science
behind it and everything.

00:46:51.410 --> 00:46:54.954
But maybe for some other sports,
some of the athletes are just--

00:46:54.954 --> 00:46:56.370
they think that
what they're doing

00:46:56.370 --> 00:46:59.250
is the way the
athlete should do,

00:46:59.250 --> 00:47:00.910
but it actually isn't the way.

00:47:00.910 --> 00:47:03.570
So I think it's really
the culture of the sport

00:47:03.570 --> 00:47:07.060
and how the athlete
grows up in the sport.

00:47:07.060 --> 00:47:08.630
I wouldn't say we
are super athletes,

00:47:08.630 --> 00:47:11.920
but at least we wake up
at 5:00, we sleep on time,

00:47:11.920 --> 00:47:12.890
we sleep at 10:00.

00:47:12.890 --> 00:47:15.100
But there are some
athletes who go for supper,

00:47:15.100 --> 00:47:17.550
and sleep at 2:00
in certain spots.

00:47:17.550 --> 00:47:20.701
And maybe that's
why they're not--

00:47:20.701 --> 00:47:22.450
THERESA GOH: I think
it's very individual.

00:47:22.450 --> 00:47:24.130
YIP PIN XIU: Yeah,
it's very individual.

00:47:24.130 --> 00:47:28.610
So I can't tell if it's from an
individual, or from a country,

00:47:28.610 --> 00:47:29.521
or from a sport.

00:47:29.521 --> 00:47:30.937
THERESA GOH: But
I think that it's

00:47:30.937 --> 00:47:35.710
also because swimming is
so marketable and so high

00:47:35.710 --> 00:47:38.120
profile for weather--

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:40.680
SPEAKER: We're outdoors
here all the time.

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:41.550
That helps, right?

00:47:41.550 --> 00:47:42.466
THERESA GOH: Oh, yeah.

00:47:42.466 --> 00:47:45.310
And there's a lot of
pools in Singapore.

00:47:45.310 --> 00:47:51.526
It helps when a country invests
more in a certain sport.

00:47:51.526 --> 00:47:55.384
Triathlon is getting hot.

00:47:55.384 --> 00:47:59.040
And a lot more people are
competing in triathlon.

00:47:59.040 --> 00:48:02.490
And it really depends on
what people know is out there

00:48:02.490 --> 00:48:05.026
and what you're exposed to.

00:48:05.026 --> 00:48:07.740
SPEAKER: So I just wanted to say
a huge thank you to both of you

00:48:07.740 --> 00:48:08.490
for coming in.

00:48:08.490 --> 00:48:11.540
[APPLAUSE]

